<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06040018 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06040018 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; CUTTING UP -- Inventor Michael Nolan, 12, ofDedham, Mass., explains his Kwik N'EZ Pizza Cutter on Friday.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  UNUSUAL; PRODUCT; SHOW; BOSTON; SCIENCE; MUSEUM  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  If you dream of being a big leaguer but have a minor league swing, 10-year-oldKevin Sullivan has built a baseball pitching machine even a 7-year-old couldmaster.;    And if you've ever tried reading in bed but found turning thepages a chore, 80-year-old Richard Stewart has come to the rescue with his&quot;book tee.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  INVENTORS STRUT THEIR BEST STUFFCHANGEABLE PUPPET TO 'BOOK TEE,' IT'S HERE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Such products of creative minds, whether practical, whimsical or just plainodd, can be found at the Museum of Science's annual Inventors Weekend, whichopened Friday. The inventors are diverse in age but have a common drive.;   &quot;My wife complains I should be out making money, but this has become such aninfatuating thing, it's hard not to do it all the time,&quot; said Paul Dupont,48.;    Sponsored by the Inventors Association of New England, the event began13 years ago as a Friday evening science program and has expanded since then.;   Dupont shelved his job as a photographer to create the &quot;unique, furry,interchangeable toy system,&quot; known as UFITS.;    It's either a faceless puppethead or a hat you wear that has a surface that takes an array of colorfulattachments. UFITS includes cloth eyes, ears, noses and other appendages thatstick like Velcro to make an infinite variety of muppetlike characters.;   Stewart, of Westbury, Conn., found reading and inventing helped to occupy histime after he retired as president of the American Brass Co. His &quot;book tee&quot;solved the discomforts of reading in bed.;    The tee holds the book in asmall wooden frame with pegs. A light from below illuminates the pages.Stewart admitted he spent five years perfecting the device.;    Fifth-graderKevin Sullivan's pitching machine was a labor of love.;    With a little helpfrom Dad, the youngster nailed an aluminum tube atop a sawhorse and attached aspring and screwdrivers for levers to create a catapult that pitches balls 10to 12 feet.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  TONY ROGERS, Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Boston  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910209  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  13E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  341  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday February 9, 199100040018,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>